{"parse":{"title":"John Wilson (Caddo)","pageid":24340483,"revid":853022071,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:202px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:John-wilson.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/John-wilson.jpg/200px-John-wilson.jpg\" width=\"200\" height=\"250\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/John-wilson.jpg/300px-John-wilson.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/John-wilson.jpg/400px-John-wilson.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"471\" data-file-height=\"588\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:John-wilson.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>John Wilson, Indian Territory, ca. 1900<sup id=\"cite_ref-s87_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-s87-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></div></div></div>\n<p><b>\"John Wilson</b> the Revealer of Peyote\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  (c.1845&#8211;1901) was a <a href=\"/wiki/Caddo\" title=\"Caddo\">Caddo</a>-<a href=\"/wiki/Lenape\" title=\"Lenape\">Delaware</a>-<a href=\"/wiki/French_people\" title=\"French people\">French</a> medicine man who introduced the <a href=\"/wiki/Peyote\" title=\"Peyote\">Peyote</a> plant into a religion, became a major leader in the <a href=\"/wiki/Ghost_Dance\" title=\"Ghost Dance\">Ghost Dance</a>, and introduced a new peyote ceremony with teachings of Christ.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> John Wilson's Caddo name was <b>Nishk\u00fb'ntu</b>, meaning \"Moon Head.\"\n</p><p>Though he was of half-Delaware descent, quarter-blood <a href=\"/wiki/French_American\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"French American\">French</a>, and quarter-blood Caddo, John Wilson spoke only the <a href=\"/wiki/Caddo_language\" title=\"Caddo language\">Caddo language</a> and identified only as a Caddo.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> He is believed to have been born in 1845, when his band of Caddo were still living in <a href=\"/wiki/Texas\" title=\"Texas\">Texas</a>. They were driven into <a href=\"/wiki/Indian_Territory\" title=\"Indian Territory\">Indian Territory</a> in 1859.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Stewart_1987_86_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Stewart_1987_86-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Wilson, being interested in religion and only known as a <a href=\"/wiki/Medicine_man\" title=\"Medicine man\">medicine man</a>, sought out a path to be a <a href=\"/wiki/Peyote_roadman\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Peyote roadman\">peyote roadman</a> in 1880.<sup id=\"cite_ref-s86_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-s86-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> As the <a href=\"/wiki/Ghost_Dance\" title=\"Ghost Dance\">Ghost Dance</a> ceremonies regained popularity in Oklahoma, he became one of its most active leaders in the Indian Territory.\n</p><p>During a two-week period, Wilson consumed peyote for spiritual reasons and said he was shown essential astronomical symbols representing the life of Jesus Christ. These messages became part of his own teaching, which nevertheless remained reliant purely on peyote. He recalled that Peyote spoke to him, telling him to keep indulging in, and to keep walking in its \"road\" until the day he died of the peyote to create a higher enlightenment.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Stewart_1987_86_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Stewart_1987_86-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The tribe had been exposed to the Half Moon peyote ceremony, but Wilson introduced the Big Moon ceremony to the tribe.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> The Caddo tribe remains very active in the <a href=\"/wiki/Native_American_Church\" title=\"Native American Church\">Native American Church</a> today.\n</p><p>He is the single human most known for the changes to the religious altar and the peyote ceremony. His changes to the altar, unintentionally persuaded<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify\" title=\"Wikipedia:Please clarify\"><span title=\"The text near this tag needs further explanation. (April 2017)\">further explanation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> the image of the cross in Christian churches.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Wilson died at the age of 61 in 1901.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=John_Wilson_(Caddo)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-s87-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-s87_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Stewart 87</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Thurman, Melburn (Summer 1973). \"Supplementary Material on the Life of John Wilson, \"The Revealer of Peyote<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">\"</span>\". <i>Supplementary Material on the Life of John Wilson, \"The Revealer of Peyote\"</i>. <b>20</b>. <a href=\"/wiki/JSTOR\" title=\"JSTOR\">JSTOR</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.jstor.org/stable/481447\">481447</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Supplementary+Material+on+the+Life+of+John+Wilson%2C+%22The+Revealer+of+Peyote%22&amp;rft.atitle=Supplementary+Material+on+the+Life+of+John+Wilson%2C+%22The+Revealer+of+Peyote%22&amp;rft.ssn=summer&amp;rft.volume=20&amp;rft.date=1973&amp;rft_id=%2F%2Fwww.jstor.org%2Fstable%2F481447&amp;rft.aulast=Thurman&amp;rft.aufirst=Melburn&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJohn+Wilson+%28Caddo%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:1-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:1_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Swan, Daniel (1999). <i>Peyote Religious Art: Symbols of Faith and Belief</i>. Jackson, Mississippi: University Press of Mississippi. p.&#160;30.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Peyote+Religious+Art%3A+Symbols+of+Faith+and+Belief&amp;rft.place=Jackson%2C+Mississippi&amp;rft.pages=30&amp;rft.pub=University+Press+of+Mississippi&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.aulast=Swan&amp;rft.aufirst=Daniel&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJohn+Wilson+%28Caddo%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-:0-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_4-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_4-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Stewart, Omer (1987). <i>Peyote Religion: A History</i>. Norman, Okla.: Univ. of Oklahoma Pr. p.&#160;86.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Peyote+Religion%3A+A+History&amp;rft.place=Norman%2C+Okla.&amp;rft.pages=86&amp;rft.pub=Univ.+of+Oklahoma+Pr.&amp;rft.date=1987&amp;rft.aulast=Stewart&amp;rft.aufirst=Omer&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJohn+Wilson+%28Caddo%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Stewart_1987_86-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Stewart_1987_86_5-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Stewart_1987_86_5-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Stewart, Omer (1987). <i>Peyote religion: a history</i>. Norman, Okla.: Univ. of Oklahoma Pr. p.&#160;86.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Peyote+religion%3A+a+history&amp;rft.place=Norman%2C+Okla.&amp;rft.pages=86&amp;rft.pub=Univ.+of+Oklahoma+Pr.&amp;rft.date=1987&amp;rft.aulast=Stewart&amp;rft.aufirst=Omer&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJohn+Wilson+%28Caddo%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-s86-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-s86_6-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Stewart 86</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-7\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Bailey, Garrick. <i>Handbook of North American Indians, volume 2: Indians in contemporary society</i>. Smithsonian Institution. p.&#160;320.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Handbook+of+North+American+Indians%2C+volume+2%3A+Indians+in+contemporary+society&amp;rft.pages=320&amp;rft.pub=Smithsonian+Institution&amp;rft.aulast=Bailey&amp;rft.aufirst=Garrick&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJohn+Wilson+%28Caddo%29\"